Hello,

For now, tasks.json allows only one command to be set.
It would be great to be able to have multiple commands, one for each tool something like this:

``` json
{
    "taskCommands": [
        {
            "command": "npm",
            "isShellCommand": true,
            "suppressTaskName": true,
            "showOutput": "always",
            "args": ["run"],
            "tasks": [
                {
                    "taskName": "npm:test",
                    // Make this the default build command.
                    "isBuildCommand": true,
                    // Show the output window only if unrecognized errors occur.
                    "args": [
                        "debug:test"
                    ]
                },
 {
                    "taskName": "npm:test2",
                    // Make this the default build command.
                    "isBuildCommand": true,
                    // Show the output window only if unrecognized errors occur.
                    "args": [
                        "debug:test2"
                    ]
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "command": "gulp",
            "isShellCommand": true,
            "suppressTaskName": true,
            "showOutput": "always",
            "args": [],
            "tasks": [
                {
                    "taskName": "gulp:test",
                    // Make this the default build command.
                    "isBuildCommand": true,
                    // Show the output window only if unrecognized errors occur.
                    "args": [
                        "debug:test"
                    ]
                }
            ]
        }
    ],
    "version": "0.1.0"
}
```

I hope you will take my request into consideration and hope this will help to enhance vscode.

Thank you in advance for your feedback.

- VSCode Version:  0.10.8 (0.10.8)
- OS Version: OS X EL Capitan 10.11

Steps to Reproduce:
1. Select the try block in following the code
2. Hit `tab`
3. Hit `Command+z`

Code:

```
function discoverTimeZone(lead, phone) {
    try {
        lead.timezone = timezoneHelper.getTimeZoneForNumber(lead[phone]);
    } catch (e) {
        lead.penalty = 1;
    }
}
```

This bug happens in other pieces of code, there is no way of undo the change with `Command+z` which makes it even worse. `Command+Shift+z` also does not help.

The workaround is to pray you saved the file in the right time, close the file from the recent files, pray once more, and open the file again.

![vsbug](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/4248124/13905674/74a85bb6-eea5-11e5-8a4e-7bb00e4027c0.gif)

Its even worse when the block of code is bigger, the code is left much more messed up. The above example you can still make sense of whats left of the code.

- VSCode Version: 0.10.11
- OS Version: OSX

I am in the process of writing a html select ui element (I will be opening a PR for this eventually), however I am having an issue getting the value of the dropdown on a change event.

The onchange function is below.  This issue is e.target.value is null because it is not defined on `EventTarget`.  I have tried fetching the changed value via `this.$select.attr('value')` but that returns null as well.  Is there a better way to structure this or what am I doing wrong here or can we update the core EventType to have the property `value` on it?

```
 this.$select.on(['change'], (e: Event, b: Builder) => {
    console.log(e.target.attr('value'));
});
```

Changing it to the following works and the value of the select is returned but the linter throws errors on it because `value` is not defined on `EventTarget`.  I guess a dirty hack here would excluding it from the linter, what would be the correct syntax for this?

```
 this.$select.on(['change'], (e: Event, b: Builder) => {
    console.log(e.target.value);
});
```

I also tried the following but the property value is not defined on HTMLElement.

```
this.$select.on(['change'], (e: Event, b: Builder) => {
    this._opts.onChange(b.currentElement.value);
});
```

The code I have for the dropdown is below.

```
/*---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 *  Copyright (c) Microsoft Corporation. All rights reserved.
 *  Licensed under the MIT License. See License.txt in the project root for license information.
 *--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------*/

'use strict';

import 'vs/css!./select';

import {Builder, $} from 'vs/base/browser/builder';
import {Widget} from 'vs/base/browser/ui/widget';

export interface SelectOption {
    value: string;
    display: string;
}

export interface ISelectOpts {
    className: string;
    options?: SelectOption[];
    defaultOption: SelectOption;
}

export class Select extends Widget {

    /*protected*/ $el: Builder;
    private _opts: ICheckboxOpts;
    public dropdown: HTMLElement;
    private $select: Builder;

    private _checked: boolean;

    constructor(container: HTMLElement, opts: ISelectOpts) {
        super();
        this._opts = opts;

        this.$el = $('.select').appendTo(container);

        this.$select = $('select');
        this.$select.addClass(this._opts.className);

        let option1 = $('option').appendTo(this.$select);
        option1.value(opts.defaultOption.value);
        option1.text(opts.defaultOption.display);

        if (opts.options !== undefined && opts.options.length !== 0) {
            for (var i = 0; i < opts.options.length; i++) {
                var option = opts.options[i];
                let optionElement = $('option').appendTo(this.$select);
                optionElement.value(option.value);
                optionElement.text(option.display);
            }
        }

        this.$select.on(['change'], (e: Event, b: Builder) => {
            console.log(e.target.attr('value'));
        });

        this.$el.append(this.$select);
    }
}
```
